00:42:20.959 --> 00:42:26.320
We do use HL7, not FHIR yet, given that they have legacy systems.

00:42:26.320 --> 00:42:34.479
For those who don't know, HL7 and FHIR are actually communication protocols between healthcare

00:42:34.479 --> 00:42:35.520
systems.

00:42:35.520 --> 00:42:36.959
So it's a messaging system.

00:42:37.439 --> 00:42:43.840
HL7 is more text-based, while FHIR is more semi-structured based JSON XML.

00:42:45.439 --> 00:42:49.919
We do have our HL7 system, but we're not using any external tools.

00:42:49.919 --> 00:42:54.879
We actually just grab the messages that we're interested in and parse them ourselves.

00:42:55.919 --> 00:42:56.719
So it's in-house.

00:42:59.199 --> 00:42:59.679
Okay.

00:43:00.080 --> 00:43:06.639
Something that is related to those where we have some, there might be some HL7 in there.

00:43:06.639 --> 00:43:08.719
If not, there will be FHIR in the future.

00:43:09.840 --> 00:43:14.719
In our medical imaging platform that we're building up, we're using something called

00:43:14.719 --> 00:43:15.280
XNet.

00:43:15.280 --> 00:43:21.120
XNet is a big suite to help organize a lot of medical imaging data and projects.

00:43:21.120 --> 00:43:26.080
So we have a lot of data, a lot of data, a lot of data, a lot of data, a lot of data,

00:43:26.080 --> 00:43:29.520
organize a lot of medical imaging data and projects.

00:43:31.040 --> 00:43:36.719
That is one very specific open source tool that we're using to communicate with the imaging

00:43:36.719 --> 00:43:40.639
systems and the different scanners that are available.

00:43:43.280 --> 00:43:47.679
That's not a specific messaging tool, but they have embedded in there a lot of different

00:43:47.679 --> 00:43:52.719
messaging protocols like RISC, PACS, RISC for communicating with PACS.

00:43:53.360 --> 00:43:56.879
I believe they're going to have FHIR in there soon, but I'm not positive.

00:43:58.719 --> 00:43:59.199
Thank you.

